Boil a large #pot{} of salted @water{to taste} for the @dried linguine{180%grams}.

When boiling, add the linguine to the water and bring back to the boil.

Cook until softened, ~{12%minutes}.

Once cooked, drain in a #colander{} and pop back in the pot, off the heat.

Drizzle with @oil{to taste} and stir through to prevent sticking.

> TIP: If you're in a hurry you can boil the water in your kettle.

Meanwhile, place a large pan over high heat with a drizzle of @oil{to taste}.

Once hot, add the @Irish beef strips{250%grams} and season with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste}.

Fry until browned, shifting as they colour, ~{2-3%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash hands and equipment after handling raw meat and its packaging. Meat is safe to eat when the outside is browned.

Once cooked, remove from the pan, set aside and cover to keep warm.

Meanwhile, halve the @bell pepper{1} and discard the core and seeds. Slice into thin strips.

Once empty, give the pan a wipe, then return to high heat with a drizzle of @oil{to taste}.

Once the oil is hot, add the pepper and fry until softened, ~{3-4%minutes}. Continue to stir while it cooks.

In the final min of cooking time, add the @Cajun spice mix{2%sachets} and fry until fragrant, ~{1%minute}.

Stir in the @passata{1%pack}, @creme fraiche{65%grams}, @beef stock{1%sachet}, @red wine jus{1%sachet}, @sugar{1/2%tsp} and @water{75%ml}.

> Double the water and sugar for 4p.

Simmer for ~{6-8%minutes}.

Add a splash of water if the sauce is too thick. Season to taste with salt and pepper.

Just before serving, stir the beef strips and drained pasta into the sauce.

Toss well and season to taste with salt and pepper, if required.

Share the Cajun pasta between plates.

Finish by sprinkling over the @grated Italian style hard cheese{25%grams}.